The Dataset

Given a dataset that looks like this

How would you group these points?

Lets try clustering it!

Previously, we learned about 2 methods of clustering:

  • K-means clustering
  • Spectral clustering

Lets take a look at how these methods would group the given dataset.

K-means clustering plot

The clusters here arent so accurate. Like we learned in class, kmeans() usually finds clusters that are spherical and non-overlapping, hence it doesnt capture nested clusters like the concentric ovals above.

Spectral clustering plot

The spectral clustering output for automatically chosen parameters isnt so accurate either

Spectral clustering with sigma = 500

By adjusting the sigma parameters, we can get a better output.

Results

The results are much better, but not perfect.

Notice that

  • You have to adjust the sigma parameter to obtain the best clusters.
    • With multivariate datasets, you wont be able to visualize your plots to check if the clusters look appropriate.
  • The clusters include noise (ie. outliers).

What if we told you theres a better clustering method for this dataset?

DBSCAN clustering plot

Lets take a look at how the DBSCAN method performs!

This method managed to not only successfully group each of the visible clusters, but also identified the ‘noise points’ (that is, points that dont belong to any cluster)!

Clustering with DBSCAN
